                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	New Delhi, Dec. 21 (PTI): Over 1,500 prisoners, including 60 women, lodged in different jails across the country died during 2008-09, according to the National Human Rights Commission.           
	Jails in Uttar Pradesh reported the highest number of deaths at 287. As many as 98 inmates died in Bengal. Over 90 per cent were natural deaths while the rest were attributed to suicide, murder, assault, firing and negligence by jail personnel.                  
	Lucknow (PTI): A constable assigned to guard an officer in the staff of Mayavati was shot dead a few metres away from the Uttar Pradesh chief ministers house on Monday. The assailants took away the policemans carbine and 20 cartridges. Passers-by spotted the constable lying near a cycle track.                  
	Meerut (PTI): An army jawan who allegedly shot dead his two colleagues for not granting leave and was on the run has been arrested, police said. Vivek Sharma, a resident of Muzaffarnagar, was arrested from Bhola village near here.                  
	New Delhi: A Delhi court has granted police two more months to chargesheet Maoist leader Khobad Ghandy and rejected his bail plea. The court accepted the polices plea that the investigation could not be completed within the prescribed 90-day limit that expired on Sunday.                  
	Srinagar (PTI): Two Kashmiri youths, who crossed the Line of Control almost two decades ago for arms training, returned and surrendered in Baramulla on Monday, police said.          
	Abdul Rashid Chopan of Waripora-Magam village and Mohammad Altaf Hajam of Chandilora, came to Kashmir with their Pakistani wives and children.                  
	Chennai (PTI): The coast guard, the navy and police have launched a joint drill to test their preparedness in dealing with 26/11-style attacks. Codenamed Operation Rakshak, the drill saw five sailors posing as terrorists and tried to enter Chennai but were caught.
                                                                                                                                              
